english:
  title: A Poem Bidding Farewell to Envoy Lu, Official of the Ministry of Rites, Upon His Return
  author: Byeon Gyeyoang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    How majestic is the throne of Ming—it brings all under heaven into harmony, and none from distant seas to near shores escape being subjects of the realm. The Son of Heaven, inheriting the mandate eternal and vast, cultivates virtue while laying aside arms, extending equal benevolence to all beneath heaven. Thus in the eleventh month of the second year of Jianwen, on the fifteenth day, he dispatched Official Lu of the Ministry of Rites, accompanied by Lin, a master of ceremony, bearing imperial decrees and bestowing upon us historical records and silken tribute. When spring arrived in the following year, on the sixth day of the second month, our lord went forth with his ministers to receive them beyond the palace gates. With banners unfurled on either side and drums sounding in procession, the envoy was led to the inner court, where all bowed and rose in reverence, dancing in celebration and crying "Long live the Emperor" three times—such was the solemnity of their greeting, showing their respect for the celestial command.

    Official Lu possessed a refined bearing and composed demeanor. His words were gentle, his countenance serene. In all his movements and deportment, he showed dignified grace. Moreover, he was adorned with the learning of poetry, history, and the Six Arts, so that all who beheld his form or heard his words felt boundless admiration and affection. Small wonder, then, that encountering such enlightened rulership and serving in the Spring Ministry, his reputation should spread throughout the realm. His mission as an envoy is but a minor matter.

    Our scholars and officials, who rejoiced at his arrival, now grieve at his departure. Many have composed verses to comfort him on his long journey, and they have asked me to write this preface. I reflect that in our Eastern lands, since the days when Kija first taught his Eight Commandments, our customs have upheld integrity and shame, and we have ever sought to emulate the Middle Kingdom. Generation upon generation has observed the rites of serving those above us. Now in our Joseon, this devotion has grown even more sincere and obedient. The Son of Heaven praises us for this, and his edicts come with warmth and care. His gifts are bestowed in abundance—such is the depth of his grace. Our feeling of gratitude must grow ever deeper, and our reverence in fulfilling our duties ever more scrupulous.

    In days to come, should Official Lu stand in the halls of the palace, addressing the Son of Heaven directly, let him relay the sincerity of our remote people with utmost clarity, so that the transformative influence spreading eastward may reach unto the boundless future. Let near and far become one harmonious whole, all united in shared flourishing. This is the work that awaits him, and this is what we scholars and officials hope for. Let him remember this well.

    As for the hardships of the distant road and the sorrow of parting—these are common to all humankind. Yet a true gentleman, understanding the weight of duty, does not trouble his heart with such concerns. Why should I mention these to one like Official Lu?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Kija (箕子): Legendary sage who founded Gojoseon and is credited with establishing foundational teachings that influenced Korean civilization and values.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Six Arts (六藝): Ritual, music, archery, charioteering, calligraphy, and mathematics—the traditional disciplines of classical East Asian learning.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Spring Ministry (春官): The Ministry of Rites, so called because it corresponds to spring in the cosmological order of imperial ministries.'
